sinless.doc:
This code tries to cure the following AI sins:

  • AI tools, that require too much data, are hard to commission
  • AI tools, that cannot explain themselves, do not permit transparency and accountability
  • AI tools, that are needlessly complicated, waste CPU time and people time (and are hard to understand, test, and extend)
  • AI tools, used off the shelf without tuning, are sub-optimal

To that end, we try:

  • Use semi-supervised learning to reduce the commission costs (i.e. use fewer labels from the domain)
  • Use symbolic AI tools that generate rules describing regions where concusions hold.
  • Use epsilon domination to stop needlessly explore spurious details
  • Use all the above in Hyperparameter optimizers so you can optimize the tool.

Does this solve all the problems of AI? Of course not. But at least its a start. And as St. Bernard of Clairvaux used to say: "A saint is not someone who never sins, but one who sins less and less frequently and gets up more and more quickly"

sinless.Skip.doc: Column: Make something that ignores everything it sees.

sinless.Num.doc: Column: Numeric counters. This is a reservoir sampler; i.e. after a fixed number of items, new items replace older ones, selected at random.

sinless.Num.add.doc: Update: Keep a representative sample of the x values as well as the lo and hi value seen so far.

sinless.Num.per.doc: Query: Return the item that is p-th beteeen lo and hi

sinless.Num.var.doc: Query: variability. As well know, plus or minus (1,2) sd is (66%,95%) of the area under the normal curve. Another number of interest is that plus or minus 1.28 sd is 90% of the mass. This means that one standard deviation is 90% of the mass divided by (1.28*2)=2.56. Hence, to compute something analogous to sd from any distribution, sort it and look at the 90th and 10th percentile.

sinless.Row.ys.doc: Query: the goal values of this row

sinless.Sample.clone.doc: Copy: return a new sample with same structure as self

sinless.Sample.header.doc: Creation: Create columns. Store dependent and independent columns in x and y

sinless.Sample.load.doc: Creation: Load data from a csv file in a Data instance.

sinless.Sample.row.doc: Update: Turn lst into either a header (if it is row0) or a row (for every other line).

distance.Sample.polarize.doc: Distance: Separate rows via their distance to two distant points.

discrete.Sym.discretize.doc: Query: Return values seen in i is good and j is bad

discrete.Num.discretize.doc: Query: Return values seen in i is good and j is bad

discrete.unsuper.doc: Discretization: divide lst into bins of at least size big, that span more than iota

discrete.merge.doc: Discretization: merge adjacent bins if they do not reduce the variability.

cli.cli.doc:
(1) Execute a command-line parse that uses dict keys as command line flags (so expect dict values to be tuples (type, defaultValue,help));
(2) Define switches for defaults that re False;
(3) If keys repeat, make the second one upper case.
